\title{Claim Audit: bcf-0001 and bcf-0002}
\taxon{reference}
\author{monaduck1069}
\date{2026-04-03}
\tag{standards}
\tag{audit}

\p{Audit of claims in the root forest page (bcf-0001) and manifesto (bcf-0002) against the classification framework (std-0002).}

\subtree{\title{Claim: "Shitty signal is better than no signal"}
\p{\strong{Class:} A (philosophical position).}
\p{\strong{Status:} Correctly framed as an axiom in bcf-0002 ("Axiom Zero"). No change needed, but the repetition in bcf-0001 lacks the axiom framing. Add "Our design axiom:" prefix in bcf-0001.}}

\subtree{\title{Claim: "$10 BCI with noise is infinitely more useful"}
\p{\strong{Class:} B (empirical claim disguised as axiom).}
\p{\strong{Issue:} "Infinitely more useful" is an empirical claim about utility. The ratio argument ("1:0") is clever but asserts that zero-access has zero utility, which is defensible, while also implying that noisy signal has positive utility, which needs evidence.}
\p{\strong{Fix:} Add a footnote or sibling tree with session data: how many self-serve readings have been conducted, what fraction of participants could identify their alpha rhythm, what the average impedance was. Even N=20 grounds this.}}

\subtree{\title{Claim: "The full-scale instantiation of Victor and Iannini's communal science lab"}
\p{\strong{Class:} B (empirical claim).}
\p{\strong{Issue:} Claims to fully instantiate a vision described in a published paper. Victor and Iannini have not endorsed this characterization.}
\p{\strong{Fix:} Change to "BCI Factory is inspired by and attempts to instantiate the four values identified in..." or obtain explicit endorsement.}}

\subtree{\title{Claim: LIFU for transcranial neuromodulation}
\p{\strong{Class:} C (safety-relevant).}
\p{\strong{Issue:} Listed as a capability without safety parameters, device specifications, or ITRUSST conformance documentation.}
\p{\strong{Fix:} Either remove until parameters are documented per std-0003, or add a subtree with device model, acoustic parameters, and safety protocol.}}

\subtree{\title{Claim: "Actual electrodes on actual heads... This is wet science"}
\p{\strong{Class:} A + C hybrid.}
\p{\strong{Issue:} The philosophical framing ("wet science") is Class A. The implication that electrode contact is safe and effective is Class C.}
\p{\strong{Fix:} Add technical reference: OpenBCI Cyton uses ADS1299 (24-bit, 250 SPS, input bias current < 200 pA). Electrode-skin interface impedance target: < 20 kOhm. Ten20 paste is FDA-listed (510(k) K990498).}}

\subtree{\title{Claim: "The marginal cost... should approach zero"}
\p{\strong{Class:} B (empirical claim about economics).}
\p{\strong{Issue:} No cost model provided. Hardware, consumables (paste, towels), electricity, and space rent are nonzero.}
\p{\strong{Fix:} Publish the actual per-session cost breakdown. Even a rough estimate (headset amortization + paste + operator time) grounds this.}}

\subtree{\title{Claim: Motion artifacts "destroy the cocycle condition"}
\p{\strong{Class:} B (empirical claim using mathematical formalism).}
\p{\strong{Issue:} The sheaf-theoretic framing (cocycle condition) is not standard in EEG artifact literature. No citation connects motion artifacts to cocycle failure.}
\p{\strong{Fix:} Either cite the specific sheaf-theoretic pipeline paper (bci-0001) that defines the cocycle condition for EEG, or replace with standard language: "motion artifacts introduce inconsistencies across electrode channels."}}
